NPC patrol is a **looping flow** through waypoints:

```
[NPC] ──walks to──→ [Point A] ──walks to──→ [Point B]
  ↑                                            │
  └────────────────────walks to────────────────┘
```

Here's how to build it:

```holo
composition "Village" {

  // The waypoints (invisible markers)
  orb WP_1 { position: [0, 0, 0], traits: ["waypoint"] }
  orb WP_2 { position: [10, 0, 0], traits: ["waypoint"] }
  orb WP_3 { position: [10, 0, 10], traits: ["waypoint"] }
  orb WP_4 { position: [0, 0, 10], traits: ["waypoint"] }

  // The NPC with patrol behavior
  template "Villager" {
    state {
      speed: 2
      current_waypoint: 0
      patrol_route: []
      paused: false
    }

    action walk_to_next() {
      if (this.paused) return

      let target = this.patrol_route[this.current_waypoint]
      this.move_toward(target.position, this.speed)

      // Reached waypoint? Go to next
      if (distance(this.position, target.position) < 0.5) {
        this.current_waypoint = (this.current_waypoint + 1) % this.patrol_route.length
        this.wait(1000)  // Pause briefly at each point
      }
    }

    action wait(ms) {
      this.paused = true
      after(ms) { this.paused = false }
    }
  }

  object "Guard" using "Villager" {
    position: [0, 0, 0]
    patrol_route: [WP_1, WP_2, WP_3, WP_4]  // Square patrol
  }

  logic {
    // The movement loop
    every(100) {
      for (npc in Villagers) {
        npc.walk_to_next()
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**The flow cycle:**
```
      ┌──→ [WP_1] ──→ [WP_2] ──┐
      │                        │
[Guard]                        ↓
      │                        │
      └──← [WP_4] ←── [WP_3] ←─┘
```

Want to make it more interesting? I can add:
- **Random routes** - pick a random next waypoint
- **Stopping to chat** - pause when player approaches
- **Different speeds** - run vs walk sections
- **Look around** - pause and rotate at waypoints

Nice! That adds a **branch** to the flow - proximity detection:

```
[Guard] ──walking──→ [Waypoints]
   │
   └──player near?──→ [Stop & Face Player]
```

Here's the updated logic:

```holo
template "Villager" {
  state {
    speed: 2
    current_waypoint: 0
    patrol_route: []
    paused: false
    notice_range: 4  // How close before they notice you
  }

  action walk_to_next() {
    // NEW: Check for player first
    if (this.player_nearby()) {
      this.react_to_player()
      return  // Don't continue patrol
    }

    if (this.paused) return

    let target = this.patrol_route[this.current_waypoint]
    this.move_toward(target.position, this.speed)

    if (distance(this.position, target.position) < 0.5) {
      this.current_waypoint = (this.current_waypoint + 1) % this.patrol_route.length
      this.wait(1000)
    }
  }

  action player_nearby() {
    return distance(this.position, Player.position) < this.notice_range
  }

  action react_to_player() {
    // Stop walking
    this.stop()

    // Turn to face player
    this.look_at(Player.position)

    // Optional: say something
    if (!this.greeted) {
      this.say(this.greeting)
      this.greeted = true
    }
  }
}

object "Guard" using "Villager" {
  position: [0, 0, 0]
  patrol_route: [WP_1, WP_2, WP_3, WP_4]
  greeting: "Halt! State your business."
  greeted: false
}

logic {
  every(100) {
    for (npc in Villagers) {
      npc.walk_to_next()
    }
  }

  // Reset greeting when player leaves
  on_player_exit_range("Guard", 4) {
    Guard.greeted = false
    Guard.say("Move along.")
  }
}
```

**The flow now has two paths:**

```
[Guard patrolling]
        │
    check proximity
        │
   ┌────┴────┐
   │         │
player     no player
 nearby      │
   │         │
   ↓         ↓
[STOP]   [CONTINUE]
face      to next
player   waypoint
greet
```

Now your guard feels alive - patrolling but aware of the player!

Great question! Think of organization as **clustering nodes** in your graph.

**Bad organization (flat mess):**
```
[tree1][tree2][rock1][enemy1][npc1][tree3][door1][rock2][enemy2]...
(everything at the same level - hard to manage)
```

**Good organization (grouped clusters):**
```
[World]
   │
   ├── [Environment]
   │       ├── [Trees] ── tree1, tree2, tree3
   │       └── [Rocks] ── rock1, rock2
   │
   ├── [Characters]
   │       ├── [NPCs] ── shopkeeper, guard
   │       └── [Enemies] ── goblin1, goblin2
   │
   └── [Interactables]
           ├── [Doors] ── door1, door2
           └── [Chests] ── chest1, chest2
```

**Use spatial_groups to cluster:**

```holo
composition "Big Village" {

  // === ENVIRONMENT GROUP ===
  spatial_group "Environment" {
    // Sub-group for trees
    spatial_group "Forest_North" {
      orb Tree_1 { position: [10, 0, 20] }
      orb Tree_2 { position: [12, 0, 22] }
      orb Tree_3 { position: [8, 0, 25] }
    }

    // Sub-group for rocks
    spatial_group "Rocky_Area" {
      orb Rock_1 { position: [30, 0, 10] }
      orb Rock_2 { position: [32, 0, 12] }
    }
  }

  // === CHARACTERS GROUP ===
  spatial_group "Characters" {
    spatial_group "Villagers" {
      object "Shopkeeper" using "NPC" { position: [0, 0, 5] }
      object "Guard" using "NPC" { position: [10, 0, 0] }
      object "Farmer" using "NPC" { position: [-15, 0, 10] }
    }

    spatial_group "Enemies" {
      object "Goblin_1" using "Enemy" { position: [50, 0, 50] }
      object "Goblin_2" using "Enemy" { position: [55, 0, 48] }
    }
  }

  // === INTERACTABLES GROUP ===
  spatial_group "Interactables" {
    orb Door_Shop { position: [0, 0, 3], leads_to: "shop_interior" }
    orb Door_House { position: [-10, 0, 5], leads_to: "house_interior" }

    orb Chest_1 { position: [5, 0, 10], gold: 50 }
    orb Chest_2 { position: [25, 0, 30], gold: 100 }
  }

  // === LOGIC BY GROUP ===
  logic {
    // Apply to all NPCs
    every(100) {
      for (npc in Villagers) {
        npc.update_behavior()
      }
    }

    // Apply to all enemies
    every(100) {
      for (enemy in Enemies) {
        enemy.check_aggro(Player)
      }
    }

    // Apply to all doors
    on_interact(Interactables.Door_*) {
      load_scene(interacted.leads_to)
    }
  }
}
```

**Benefits of grouping:**

1. **Easy iteration** - `for (tree in Forest_North)` instead of listing each tree
2. **Bulk operations** - hide/show entire groups
3. **Organized logic** - different update loops for different groups
4. **Cleaner files** - can split groups into separate files

**Pro tip - split into files:**

```holo
// main.holo
composition "Big Village" {
  import "./environment.holo"
  import "./characters.holo"
  import "./interactables.holo"
  import "./logic.holo"
}
```

That way your graph stays visually clean even with hundreds of nodes!

Let's diagnose your graph! Performance issues usually come from:

**1. Too many edge evaluations** (logic running too often)

```
❌ BAD: Checking everything every frame
[every(16)] ──checks──→ [ALL 500 objects]
```

```holo
// This is expensive!
every(16) {  // 60fps = lots of work
  for (obj in AllObjects) {  // 500 objects
    check_distance(Player, obj)  // That's 30,000 checks/second!
  }
}
```

**✅ FIX: Reduce frequency, use spatial partitioning**

```holo
// Much better
every(250) {  // 4 times per second is enough for AI
  let nearby = spatial_query(Player.position, 20)  // Only check nearby
  for (obj in nearby) {
    check_distance(Player, obj)
  }
}
```

---

**2. Too many nodes visible** (draw calls)

```
❌ BAD: 1000 individual trees
[Tree_1][Tree_2]...[Tree_1000]  // 1000 draw calls
```

**✅ FIX: Use instancing and LOD**

```holo
// Group identical objects
spatial_group "Forest" {
  instanced: true  // GPU draws all at once
  lod_distances: [50, 100, 200]  // Lower detail at distance

  // 1000 trees, but efficient
  generate_trees(1000, bounds: [-100, -100, 100, 100])
}
```

---

**3. Complex flows running always**

```
❌ BAD: All enemies always active
[Enemy_1]──AI loop──→ running
[Enemy_2]──AI loop──→ running
... (100 enemies all thinking)
```

**✅ FIX: Activate only when relevant**

```holo
template "Enemy" {
  state {
    active: false  // Start inactive
    activation_range: 30
  }
}

logic {
  // Only activate nearby enemies
  every(500) {
    for (enemy in Enemies) {
      let dist = distance(Player, enemy)
      enemy.active = (dist < enemy.activation_range)
    }
  }

  // Only run AI for active enemies
  every(100) {
    for (enemy in Enemies) {
      if (enemy.active) {
        enemy.think()  // Only nearby enemies think
      }
    }
  }
}
```

---

**4. Event spam** (too many broadcasts)

```
❌ BAD: Broadcasting every position change
on_move(anything) {
  broadcast("something_moved")  // 1000 broadcasts/second
}
```

**✅ FIX: Batch or throttle events**

```holo
// Collect changes, broadcast once
let pending_updates = []

on_move(obj) {
  pending_updates.push(obj)
}

every(100) {
  if (pending_updates.length > 0) {
    broadcast("objects_moved", pending_updates)
    pending_updates = []
  }
}
```

---

**Quick checklist:**

| Issue | Check | Fix |
|-------|-------|-----|
| Low FPS | `every()` interval | Increase to 100-500ms for AI |
| Stuttering | Object count | Use instancing, reduce unique objects |
| Lag spikes | Broadcast count | Batch/throttle events |
| Memory | Spawned objects | Despawn offscreen, object pooling |

**Debug command:**
```holo
logic {
  on_key("F3") {
    show_debug_stats()  // FPS, draw calls, active flows
  }
}
```

