Dominoes are a **linear chain flow** - each node triggers the next:

```
[Push] ──→ [D1] ──→ [D2] ──→ [D3] ──→ [D4] ──→ [D5] ──→ [End Effect]
            │        │        │        │        │
           fall    fall     fall     fall     fall
```

Here's how to build it:

```holo
composition "Domino Chain" {

  template "Domino" {
    state { fallen: false }

    action fall() {
      if (this.fallen) return  // Can't fall twice

      this.fallen = true
      this.animate("topple")
      audio.play_at("domino_click", this.position)

      // Trigger the next one after a delay
      if (this.next) {
        after(200) {
          this.next.fall()
        }
      }
    }
  }

  spatial_group "DominoLine" {
    object "D1" using "Domino" { position: [0, 0, 0], next: "D2" }
    object "D2" using "Domino" { position: [0.5, 0, 0], next: "D3" }
    object "D3" using "Domino" { position: [1.0, 0, 0], next: "D4" }
    object "D4" using "Domino" { position: [1.5, 0, 0], next: "D5" }
    object "D5" using "Domino" { position: [2.0, 0, 0], next: null }
  }

  // The starting trigger
  orb StartButton {
    position: [-1, 1, 0]
    traits: ["interactive"]
  }

  logic {
    on_interact("StartButton") {
      D1.fall()  // Start the chain!
    }

    // End effect when last domino falls
    on_fallen("D5") {
      spawn_particles("celebration", D5.position)
      ui.toast("Chain complete!")
    }
  }
}
```

**The flow propagates:**
```
[Button] ──click──→ D1.fall() ──200ms──→ D2.fall() ──200ms──→ ...
```

Each domino knows its `next` neighbor - that's the edge in the graph. The delay creates the cascade effect.

