**File organization:**
```
src/
├── utils/
│   ├── math.ts        ← Pure TypeScript utilities
│   ├── events.ts      ← TypeScript event system
│   └── helpers.ts     ← Generic helpers
├── systems/
│   ├── combat.hsplus  ← HoloScript systems
│   ├── movement.hsplus
│   └── inventory.hsplus
├── entities/
│   ├── player.hsplus  ← Entity definitions
│   └── enemy.hsplus
├── scenes/
│   ├── forest.holo    ← Scene definitions
│   └── dungeon.holo
├── types/
│   └── index.ts       ← Shared TypeScript types
└── main.hsplus        ← Entry point
```

**When to use .ts vs .hsplus:**
```
Use .ts when:
├── Pure utility functions (no game logic)
├── Type definitions only
├── Third-party library wrappers
├── Node.js/backend code
└── Code shared with non-HoloScript projects

Use .hsplus when:
├── Game systems (ECS)
├── Entity definitions
├── World/scene logic
├── Code that imports .holo files
└── Code using HoloScript-specific features
```

**They compile together:**
```bash
# Compiles all .ts, .hsplus, and generates types from .holo
holoscript build

# Output:
dist/
├── utils/
│   ├── math.js
│   └── math.d.ts
├── systems/
│   ├── combat.js      ← .hsplus → .js
│   └── combat.d.ts
├── scenes/
│   └── forest.json    ← .holo → runtime format
└── main.js
```

**Bottom line:** .hsplus is a superset of TypeScript. Use .ts for generic code, .hsplus for game-specific code.
